    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-12T07:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-12T07:35:00-05:00" n="299"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d299">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.9111/24: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-12T16:00:00+03:25"
                            >January 12, 1942—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 12—5:36 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. I have advised the Iranian Government of the purport of Department’s 165,
                    December 29.<note n="41" xml:id="d299fn41">
                        <ref target="frus1941v03#pg_477">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., p. 477</ref>.</note> Both the Prime<note
                        n="42" xml:id="d299fn42">Mohammed Ali Foroughi, Iranian Prime Minister,
                        August 1941–March 1942.</note> and Foreign Ministers<note n="43"
                        xml:id="d299fn43">Ali Soheily.</note> seem deeply perturbed about the
                    situation in Azerbaijan, alleging that Soviet interference and propaganda
                    continue unabated. They express the belief that this condition might be
                    alleviated and that the Russians might perhaps be deterred from pushing a
                    Separatist movement were the United States to make a statement taking cognizance
                    of the treaty<note n="44" xml:id="d299fn44">Proposed Anglo-Soviet-Iranian Treaty
                        of Alliance.</note> and guaranteeing the independence and territorial
                    integrity of Iran. The Foreign Minister states that the Shah intends when treaty
                    is signed, which should be in a week or so, to communicate this fact to the
                    President referring in his communication to the Atlantic Charter.<note n="45"
                        xml:id="d299fn45">Joint statement by President Roosevelt and British Prime
                        Minister Churchill, August 14, 1941, <ref target="frus1941v01#pg_367">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi> 1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps"
                                >i</hi>, p. 367</ref>.</note> The reply to this telegram might
                    present a good opportunity for a statement along the lines suggested above,
                    should the Department deem such a course to be advisable. If such a statement is
                    made in reply to the Shah’s telegrams the Iranian Government would wish to have
                    permission to publish it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
